comments.text:
Dear Akash,

With all due respect, I would like to share a few thoughts.
Before any judgment is made, I want to say that I deeply follow your ideology and truly respect the narratives you stand for. I believe in secularism with all my heart. I firmly believe that our Muslim friends and neighbors of ou country are not responsible for such attacks, nor should they ever be held collectively accountable.

However, one thing that continues to trouble me is that no one talks openly about the extremist mindset that exists within certain sections, or the misrepresentation of Islam by some moulvis from the pulpits of mosques.
I don’t know about others, but personally, I feel exhausted trying to stand for secularism these days. It’s heartbreaking when it feels like there is no willingness for reform. Many still cling to a medieval mindset.

A small observation from my side: during our childhood, we rarely saw burqas in our town. Our Muslim friends didn’t attend madrasas, they studied with us in regular schools. Today, in 2025, walking down the streets often feels like walking somewhere in Bangladesh or Pakistan; so many women are now in burqas, and the number of madrasas has perhaps exceeded the number of government schools in the district.
I know we should not judge people by their dress or where they study. But when you actually talk to them, you often realize how backward and rigid their thinking has become. And yet, no one talks about the urgent need for reform. In fact, if anyone dares to try, they risk their own life. Everyone seems more focused on appearing religious than on promoting real progress.

It’s not just RSS supporters who are “andh bhakts”; there are “andh bhakts” on the other side as well maybe with a different name in Urdu. Sadly, with time, it feels like we are all moving backwards. And in the end, people get the government they deserve.

Maybe you missed:

Decades of coups: Ayub Khan, Zia-ul-Haq, Musharraf — because nothing says “trustworthy army” like repeatedly toppling your own elected government.


Pakistani Army's reputation was a meme long before TikTok even existed.

comments.text:
@RoysOdyssey  You sound exhausted trying to "stand for secularism," but history reminds us:
Secularism dies when one side refuses reform while the other side keeps pretending everything is just about "respect".

It’s cute that you’re surprised about the rising medieval mindset —
maybe you missed how the Deobandi movement (1866) and Tableeghi Jamaat (1926) were literally founded to push society backwards into strict orthodoxy?
It’s not new — it’s just faster now because cowardly liberals spent decades romanticizing regressiveness instead of confronting it.

And about burqas and madrasas? Well, Sir Syed Ahmad Khan fought the same battles in the 19th century — and guess what? He was abused and called "Kafir" by the same mentality you’re politely begging for reform today.

Newsflash:
When you cuddle medieval thinking in the name of “respect,” don’t cry when your streets start looking like a history museum.

You’re not exhausted because you fought the mindset.
You’re exhausted because you fed it with silence.
